  "prompt": "How many 3-digit numbers can be formed using only 1, 2, 3?",
  "response": "Let's solve this step by step:\n\n1) First, let's consider the hundreds place\n   \u2022 We can use 1, 2, or 3 in the hundreds place\n   \u2022 So we have 3 choices for the hundreds place\n\n2) For the tens place\n   \u2022 We can again use 1, 2, or 3\n   \u2022 So we have 3 choices for the tens place\n\n3) For the ones place\n   \u2022 We can again use 1, 2, or 3\n   \u2022 So we have 3 choices for the ones place\n\n4) By the multiplication principle, the total number of possible 3-digit numbers is\n   \u2022 3 \u00d7 3 \u00d7 3 = 27\n\nTherefore, 27 different 3-digit numbers can be formed using only 1, 2, 3.\n\nTo verify, these numbers would include:\n\u2022 111, 112, 113\n\u2022 121, 122, 123\n\u2022 131, 132, 133\n\u2022 211, 212, 213\n\u2022 221, 222, 223\n\u2022 231, 232, 233\n\u2022 311, 312, 313\n\u2022 321, 322, 323\n\u2022 331, 332, 333\n\nThe answer is 27.",
